-- 
U.K. Stocks Fall; Reckitt Benckiser Tumbles as CEO Steps Down

-- B y   G i l e s   B r o o m
-- 
2011-04-14T16:27:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/u-k-stocks-fall-reckitt-benckiser-tumbles-as-ceo-steps-down.html
U.K. stocks declined for the third
time in four days amid concern that peripheral European nations
will be forced to restructure their debt and as U.S. jobless-
benefit claims rose more than forecast.  Reckitt Benckiser Group Plc (RB/) , the maker of Nurofen
painkillers, slumped 7.5 percent after Chief Executive Officer
Bart Becht said he will step down.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , the
world’s largest mining company, dropped as copper fell for a
fourth day.  The  FTSE 100 Index (UKX)  lost 0.8 percent to 5,963.8 at the 4:30
p.m. close in  London , the lowest level this month. The FTSE All-
Share Index fell 0.7 percent, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index
increased 0.2 percent.  “Worries over Greece’s debt problems have returned to
haunt European markets today,” said Will Hedden, a sales trader
at IG Index in London. The disappointing U.S. jobs data “has
added to the risk-off mood on both  Wall Street  and here in
 Europe .”  More Americans unexpectedly filed first-time claims for
 unemployment insurance  last week. Applications for jobless
benefits rose 27,000 in the week ended April 9 to 412,000, the
most in two months, Labor Department figures showed today.
Economists projected claims would be little changed at 380,000,
according to the median estimate in a Bloomberg News survey.  Reckitt Retreats  Reckitt Benckiser, which also makes Vanish stain remover,
plunged 7.5 percent to 3,115 pence, the biggest drop in eight
years. The world’s biggest maker of household cleaners said
Rakesh Kapoor will replace Becht as CEO in September.  Becht, who has led the company since its creation more than
a decade ago, will stay on as a part-time adviser until
September 2012, Slough, England-based Reckitt said in a
statement today.  BHP Billiton  lost 0.9 percent to 2,518.5 pence for its
third straight decline. Copper in London dropped for a fourth
day, the longest losing streak since January, as investors
speculated that  China  may further tighten credit to damp asset
prices.  Rio Tinto Group slipped 1.3 percent to 4,350 pence. The
world’s third-largest mining company may report earnings 4
percent lower than predicted because rain curbed production of
some commodities in the first quarter, UBS AG said in a report
today. Rio may generate net income of $18 billion in 2011
compared with an earlier forecast of $18.7 billion, analysts led
by Glyn Lawcock said.  Antofagasta, ENRC  Antofagasta Plc (ANTO) , the owner of copper mines in Chile,
tumbled 3.6 percent to 1,355 pence. Eurasian Natural Resources
Corp. sank 2.3 percent to 909 pence.  A gauge of banks in the Stoxx Europe 600 Index slid 1.5
percent, the largest drop of 19 industry groups and the yield on
Greece’s 10-year bond climbed above 13 percent for the first
time since at least 1998 after German Finance Minister  Wolfgang Schaeuble  told Die Welt newspaper that the Mediterranean country
may need to restructure its debt.  Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc (RBS)  lost 1.4 percent to 43.53
pence and Barclays Bank Plc fell 2.3 percent to 301.8 pence.  Stagecoach Group Plc (SGC)  gained 5.1 percent to 228.8 pence, the
highest price in over two years, amid speculation that the
operator of the U.K.’s business commuter-rail service may
receive a takeover offer.  “We are hearing certain amount of bid speculation out
there on the company,” said Simon Clark, a trader at ETX
Capital in London. “Stock is up on good volume.”  Retailers further limited declines in the FTSE 350 Index.
 Dixons Retail Plc (DXNS)  rallied 8.4 percent to 13.18 euros and  WH
Smith Plc (SMWH)  climbed 5.4 percent to 475.1 pence.  To contact the reporter on this story:
